Data Cleaning and Sampling

  • airline_passenger_satisfaction.csv
airline = read.csv("airline_passenger_satisfaction.csv")
airline = airline %>% drop_na()
set.seed(2003)
airline_sample <- airline[sample(1:nrow(airline), 1000), ]

Dataset Summary

Airline Passenger Satisfaction

Dataset Description:

  • The dataset consists of customer satisfaction scores of 120,000+ airline passengers; we random sampled 1000 observations.

  • Our sample contains information about each passenger as well as details about their flight and flying experience.

  • Of the 24 columns, we selected five key variables to explore our questions of interest Departure and Arrival Time Convenience, Satisfaction, Type of Travel, Departure Delay, Arrival Delay.

Data Dictionary:

  • Departure and Arrival Time Convenience: Satisfaction level with the convenience of the flight departure and arrival times from 1 (lowest) to 5 (highest) - 0 means not applicable.

  • Satisfaction: Overall satisfaction level with the airline (Satisfied/Neutral or unsatisfied).

  • Type of Travel: Purpose of the flight (Business/Personal).

  • Departure Delay: Flight departure delay in minutes.

  • Arrival Delay: Flight arrival delay in minutes.

Research Question 1

How do departure and arrival delays relate to a passengers satisfaction by reason for travel?

Copy dataset and clean it to include 554 passengers with either a departure or arrival delay

data <- copy(airline_sample)
data <- data[!(data$Departure.Delay == 0 & data$Arrival.Delay == 0),]
data <- data[!(data$Departure.and.Arrival.Time.Convenience == 0),]

Graph of time convenience satisfaction and overall satisfaction by reason for travel

delay_sat <- ggplot(data, aes(Departure.and.Arrival.Time.Convenience, y = prop.table(stat(count)), fill = Type.of.Travel, label = scales::percent(prop.table(stat(count))))) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") + 
  geom_text(stat = 'count', position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = -0.5, size = 3) +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Passengers' Satisfaction by Reason for Travel",
    subtitle = "Departure and Arrival Time Satisfaction") +
  xlab('Departure and Arrival Time Convenience') + 
  ylab('Count') +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#B9D7ED", "#23628F")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(fill= "Reason for Travel") 

overall_sat <- ggplot(data, aes(Satisfaction, y = prop.table(stat(count)), fill = Type.of.Travel, label = scales::percent(prop.table(stat(count))))) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") + 
  geom_text(stat = 'count', position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = -0.5, size = 3) +
  ylim(0, 100) +
  labs(
    title = "",
    subtitle = "Overall Satisfaction") +
  xlab('Satisfaction') + 
  ylab('Count') +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#B9D7ED", "#23628F")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(fill = "Reason for Travel") 
## Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
## replace the existing scale.
ggarrange(delay_sat, overall_sat, common.legend = TRUE, legend = "bottom", widths = c(2,1.1))

Analysis:

  • The dataset was subsetted for passengers that experienced either a departure or arrival delay, which narrowed it down to 554 out of the 1000 observations. The business travellers take up 67.86% of the 554 proportion and personal travellers took up 32.14%.

  • The left barplot shows passengers that rated the flights departure and arrival time convenience from 1-5 (5 being very satisfied) and the overall trend shows that delayed passengers flying for business purposes were divided in their satisfaction from a range of 12-15%, but those flying for personal reasons seemed to not mind the delays as much with 4-5 ratings ranging from 10-12% and 1-3 having 2-5%. This makes sense as business travelers usually work on a tight schedule and may be affected by delays more then leisure travelers are.

  • The right barplot shows a more interesting trend in that business passengers were generally divided in their satisfaction with the overall flight where 57.1% of delayed passengers flying for business reasons were satisfied (including service, comfort, cleanliness, entertainment, etc) while those flying for personal reasons were either neutral or dissatisfied at nearly 93.52% of delayed passengers travelling for personal reasons. An interpretation of why this may be so is that people who do business travel fly often and not only know what to expect but also dont care much about the in-flight services. Those travelling for personal reasons may be travelling for the first time or in economy class and thus the in-flight services have a greater effect on their satisfaction level.

  • Overall, we conclude that Business travelers gave more importance to Departure and Arrival Time convenience and delays while leisure travelers care more about additional services offered to them.

Research Question 2

Relationship between Departure and Arrival Delays and how it affects a passengers satisfaction level

Copy dataset and clean it to include passengers who experienced either a departure delay and/or less than a 200 minute arrival delay

data2 <- copy(airline_sample)
data2 <- data2[(data2$Arrival.Delay<200 & data2$Departure.Delay>0 ),]

Graph showing relationship between departure and arrival delays separated by Overall Passenger Satisfaction

ggplot(data2,               
       aes(x =Arrival.Delay,           
           y =Departure.Delay)) +       
  geom_point(aes(color=Satisfaction))+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Delays in Departure and Arrival", 
       subtitle="Understanding the effect on Passenger Satisfaction",
       x="Delay in Arrival (minutes)", y="Delay in Departure (minutes)")+
  xlim(0,200)+ylim(0,200)+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Neutral or Dissatisfied" = "red", "Satisfied" = "darkgreen"))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Analysis:

  • The sample dataset was filtered to only include flights that experienced a departure delay and/or less than a 200 minute arrival delay from their scheduled arrival time for better visualization. This reduced our dataset to 426 data points but helped us reach some interesting conclusions.

  • The graph shows an expected relationship between delay in departure and delay and arrivala positive relationship; ie, the more delayed a flight;s departure is the more delayed its arrival will be. However, some of the data points near the x and y axis reflect that some flights that did experience a delay in departure, did not experience an arrival delay as it may have been covered up in flying time.

  • Another important conclusion we can make from this graph is that passengers are usually dissatisfied with their flying experience if their flight is delayed. This is seen in the graph as there are more red than green points. It is interesting to note, however, that there are a few green points even when customers experienced a significant amount of delay. This may be explained by the the delay compensations offered by the airline or other services which made their experience a pleasant one despite the delay.

  • Lastly, we see that passengers are usually satisfied if their flights delay in departure does not affect their arrival time. This is represented by the cluster of green points in the graph on the y-axis that represents a non-zero delay in departure but a 0 minute delay in arrival. On the contrary, passengers are dissatisfied if their flight departed on time/only a few minutes late but experienced a much greater delay in arrival. This is represented by the red dots near the x axis.
